{
  "texts": [
    "However, these traditional statistical methods require many a priori assumptions on the time-series prediction, such as stability, normal distribution, linear correlation, and independence.",
    "For example, AR, MA, and ARMA models are based on the assumption that time series are stationary, but in many real cases, time-series data exhibit non-stationarity.",
    "These assumptions limit the effectiveness of these traditional methods in real-world applications.As it is difficult to effectively capture the nonlinear relationships between time series with traditional statistical approaches, many researchers have studied LTSF from the perspective of machine learning (ML) [25][26][27][28][29].",
    "Support vector machines (SVMs) [30] and adaptive boosting (AdaBoost) [31] were employed in the field of TSF.",
    "They calculate data metrics, such as minimum, maximum, mean, and variance, within a sliding window as new features for prediction."
  ]
}